This paper is about dialogue state tracking, which is a subfield of natural language processing and falls under the category of computational linguistics (cs.CL). The proposed model uses self-attention and deep learning techniques, which are commonly used in artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG). The paper also discusses the performance of the model on different datasets, which relates to the subfield of statistical learning (cs.SD). Finally, the use of global and local modules in the model suggests a neural network architecture, which is a common topic in neural networks (cs.NE).
